# hilavitkutin-kit backlog

> **Type-surface reminder**: new entries use `arvo::USize` /
> `Bool` / `UFixed<N, 0, S>` instead of `usize` / `bool` / `u*`;
> `notko::Maybe` / `Outcome` instead of `Option` / `Result`;
> `hilavitkutin_str::Str` instead of `&str` / `String`. See
> `rules/type-surface.md`.

## Helper types for common Kit-composition patterns

If a real consumer surfaces a recurring Kit-shape pattern (for
example, a Kit that registers N resources from a config struct,
or a Kit that conditionally installs a sibling Kit based on a
build cfg), promote the helper to this crate. Until then, none.

The Kit trait itself is intentionally minimal. Helpers ship here
when they earn it from concrete consumer use.

## `app!` / `define_app!` macro

Parked at task #295 (P2, likely never). The macro would fold the
chain `SchedulerBuilder::new().add_kit(K1).add_kit(K2).add::<W1>()
.add::<W2>().build()` into one declarative block. Skipped this
round because:

- Bevy proves the raw builder pattern is ergonomically sufficient
  at the consumer call counts reached by viola, vehje, and similar
  hilavitkutin apps (roughly ten registrations per app).
- The macro adds complexity (declarative or proc-macro) without a
  measurable readability win at that scale.
- If a downstream consumer authors a Kit chain long enough that
  the raw form actually obscures intent, revisit #295.
